³ Praeter-condemnatis] Praeter is here put adverbially for praeter- quam, and condemnaris is the dative, being governed by liceret.—M.

⁴ Dilectum habeant] When a consul or general, by order of the se- nate, assembled the youth, and picked out such persons as they thought proper for the service, obliging them to enlist, and take the military oath3 this was called dilectum habere, and was only used in cases of necessity.—M. Not dilectum but delectum—C.
